How to search values in real time on a badly designed database?

I have a collection named Company which has the following structure:

{
    "_id" : ObjectId("57336ea1a7454c0100d889e4"),
    "currentMonth" : 62,
    "variables1": { ... },
    ...
    "variables61": { ... },
    "variables62" : {
        "name" : "Test",
        "email": "email@test.com",
         ...
    },
    "country" : "US",
}

My need is to be able to search for companies by name with up-to-date data. I don't have permission to change this data structure because many applications still use it. For the moment I haven't found a way to index these variables with this data structure, which makes the search slow.

Today each of these documents can be several megabytes in size and there are over 20,000 of them in this collection.

The system I want to implement uses a search engine to index the names of companies, but for that it needs to be able to detect changes in the collection.

MongoDB's change stream seems like a viable option but I'm not sure how to make it scalable and efficient.

Do you have any suggestions that would help me solve this problem? Any suggestion on the steps needed to set up the above system?
answer: I don't understand your question but here's some generic information:   A `v8::Local` is a reference that goes away when its handlescope goes away.   A `v8::Global` (presumably what you mean persistent) remains until the Global variable has its destructor called or `::Reset(...)`.  It is common to make a `Global<Context>`, as that's the only way to put it in a data structure to keep the context around to do stuff with it later.

answer: Well, this is a bit related to how the map-reduce framework operates internally. The framework instantiates a Mapper object, this has the map method that you defined, but since the same Mapper object applies the map method to multiple key-value pairs in the input split , it is capable of preserving the state across multiple key-value pairs inputs,a simple example of this state could be  a counter for every key it encounters. It could even load "state" data at "setup" time and preserve it(or update it) across multiple inputs.
